Hello! Doula here! Doulas can be hired for any type of birth! We are here to educate, and advocate for your decisions and preferences! I have done home births, hospital, medicated, scheduled csections, you name it. @Zoe Rudesill Well with an epidural you don't have pain anymore but it's just SUPER intense, the feeling of pressure is very overwhelming and I felt like something was stuck down there. Like a bowl movement but x 1000 and like you are constipated but at the same time feel intense waves of pressure. It was extremely unpleasant and I felt very anxious and like I couldn't do it. I preferred the pain of contractions. That being said I got an epidural at 3 cm, not because I couldn't deal with the pain anymore, it was still manageable but because I did not want to "feel everything" later on. And I'm glad I got it! Would have been so much worse if I had had to handle horrible contractions at the same time as what I described.The pain of contractions when you are more dilated is horrendous from what I hear. I mean I never understand when people are surprised by how much pain they are in during labour, I'm always like "duh, you think women screaming as if they were possessed happens for no reason" lol.

Can I just say, firstly, how amazing you were. Just the knowledge and the awareness you had throughout your labour of how to encourage labour, how to keep energised, stay hydrated. I love how natural you kept your labour, using the water and essential oils.

I love how informed your doula kept you and how low risk and natural the midwife kept the labour, my only one criticism is that if there were no concerns about the baby, then you should not have been put on the monitor with the bands around your stomach. It’s just uncomfortable, and unnecessary, though I suspect you probably didn’t care at that point! However otherwise I think your midwife was great and I love that it was just her and another midwife in the room for the birth, I hate seeing videos where the room fills up with doctors and you’ve got an OB shouting at the end of the bed for you to push. Totally unnecessary in a normal low risk birth. So I’m really happy for you.
